SIMPLE: revocation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Revocation
<hw>Rev`o*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>revocatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>r⟦eacute⟧vocation</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of calling back, or the state of being
recalled; recall.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One that saw the people bent for the <qex>revocation</qex> of
Calvin, gave him notice of their affection.</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act by which one, having the right, annuls an
act done, a power or authority given, or a license, gift, or benefit
conferred; repeal; reversal; <as>as, the <ex>revocation</ex> of an
edict, a power, a will, or a license</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Revocatory</ent>⟦br⟧
